review: The Other Bennet Sister was absolutely delightful! Janice Hadlow manages to keep the spirit of Jane Austen in her story about Mary -the poor Bennet siThe Other Bennet Sister was absolutely delightful! Janice Hadlow manages to keep the spirit of Jane Austen in her story about Mary -the poor Bennet sister who is always overlooked and not considered beautiful compared to her other sisters. The Other Bennet Sister follows the beginnings of Pride & Prejudice but from Mary's point of view and continues on following Mary in her journey of finding her own happiness and way in the world. Mrs. Bennet is the same selfish jerk of mother, Caroline Bingley is still a force to be reckoned with and many other P&P characters still play a special role in Mary's adult life. I really appreciated Hadlow's version of Mary and giving her her own stand-alone story. This is a MUST read for any Austen fan!...more

title: I'm Your Huckleberry: A Memoir
author: Kilmer, Val
my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: I am torn about my feelings on this one. I liked it but I didn't LOVE it. I have been a fan of Val Kilmer's work for a while and who he is as a personI am torn about my feelings on this one. I liked it but I didn't LOVE it. I have been a fan of Val Kilmer's work for a while and who he is as a person (as much as you can get from a memoir) is pretty much who I thought he would be. A bit vain with some humility, a lot of spiritual and over the top at times. This memoir is probably not the best he could have written, but considering all that he has been through this past decade, maybe it is?He does go through his experiences in all of his greatest movie hits and even some not so great. I think for some, he looks into the past with rose-colored glasses. Ex: The Island of Dr. Moreau. He dives into each movie almost equally, but he does give The Doors and Tombstone a little bit more concentration for good reason. He loves to love women. So be ready for his falling deeply in love with many women in this book! To give you an idea of the general feeling in this memoir through Val's movie characters. These are the ones that kept popping up in my head while reading: Iceman (Top Gun), Jim Morrison (The Doors), Thomas More (The Saint), Doc Holliday (Tombstone) and Gay Perry (Kiss Kiss Bang Bang). This could be because they are some of my favorites. Actually not true, I hated his Thomas More character in The Saint.If you like Val Kilmer, it is worth the read. However, do not expect to be wowed by it. I say this with respect to Val who I believe could have written a more amazing memoir (mine would be boring AF). I recommend just reading this book and not listening to the audio. The only narrator I enjoyed was Mare Winningham and she does not get as much narration time!...more

review: NO, I was not a fan of One Tree Hill. Just thought I would throw that out first thing! If you were a fan and want to read about her experiences on thaNO, I was not a fan of One Tree Hill. Just thought I would throw that out first thing! If you were a fan and want to read about her experiences on that show -- this is not that book. There are few mentions here and there but mostly concentrating on the negative work environment she experienced. I have been wary of reading celebrity memoirs since the last two I read were disappointing. However, this one was rather refreshing! Hilarie shares her relationship journey with Jeffrey Dean Morgan and their desire to live a more simple life. There were some very heartfelt/personal experiences that made me tear up a few times (wasn't expecting that) and their misadventures in farming moments made me crack up. Overall this book was well written and I enjoyed it. Also, be prepared to write down some of her recipes (if you get the book from the library) and yes, dandelion wine is one of them!...more

I started by reading the paperback and then transitioned to the audiobook because I saw that the brilliant Ron Perlman was the narrator. He did not disappoint. (My husband has currently commandeered the paperback) Yes, this story is crude in parts (mostly Kolya) and definitely has a "series of unfortunate events" but that is to be expected from a book set during the war. However, I loved the dynamic between Koyla and Lev and the rather odd quest that pushed the unlikely pair together. Though Kolya could be a bit much at times, I ended up not taking him too seriously. He was more of an odd comic relief. I appreciated his older brother mentality towards Lev. Poor Lev was just a kid trying to survive in a horrific world. This was a fast read for me. title: The Woman Who Would Be King: Hatshepsut's Rise to Power in Ancient Egypt
author: Cooney, Kara
my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: I had to give myself time to think about my rating/ for this one. This book was not a page-turner for me, but truthfully, most historical books I had to give myself time to think about my rating/ for this one. This book was not a page-turner for me, but truthfully, most historical books take me longer to read, so I can't give this a lower rating because it didn't grip my attention the whole time! First, I highly recommend that you listen to the audio version of this book. I started out with the paperback version but realized quickly that I was going to need someone to pronounce the Egyptian names, places, etc. Even in my head, I do not like not knowing how to correctly say a word. The author, Dr. Kathlyn Cooney, narrates the book. She is not the BEST narrator, but thanks to her, I can pronounce Hatshepsut as well as my own name :)Second, go into this book knowing that most of the book is conjecture (though scholarly). Most, if not all, of Hatshepsut's "KING" history was erased by Thutmose III. Also, Egyptians were not known for sharing incredible detail (hieroglyphics made it hard to do so) and they rarely recorded unpleasantries about people or events. Hatshepsut's story is an important one and one that deserves a place in Egyptian history. She was a woman who rose to become pharaoh of Egypt not with bloodshed but with masterful strategy. The theories as to why she was erased are an even more intriguing and an eye-opening look as to why female and not male rulers were looked down upon in Egyptian (or if we are honest ALL) history. ...more

We follow the Allbright family who move from the comforts of the city to the wilds of the Alaskan frontier on the desire of the father, Ernt Allbright, a former Vietnam POW. Kristin Hannah does an amazing job of creating the harsh and beautiful environment of the Alaskan frontier as well as the VERY small but supportive community living within in it--great character development. The Allbright family themselves are a whole other layer of the story and the father, Ernt Allbright, was a perfect parallel to their environment (unpredictable). I appreciated the truthful depiction of a family forever altered by the psychological damage of war. I wanted to give this book 5 stars but the last few chapters felt rushed and the ending was a little too perfectly wrapped up for me. review: Myths can be difficult to understand as they are supernatural fables that have no need to be realistic and often contradict each other. That being saiMyths can be difficult to understand as they are supernatural fables that have no need to be realistic and often contradict each other. That being said, Madeline Miller does an amazing job of creating a comprehensive and entertaining story of the witch-goddess CIRCE. I listened to the audio version read by British actress Perdita Weeks (Lost in Austen, Penny Dreadful) who gives Circe a perfect narrative voice. Circe is the daughter of Perse, an Oceanid nymph, and the Greek God of the Sun, Helios (Titan). Madeline Miller creates the early life of Circe, a goddess not loved by her family because she has more mortal characteristics than god-like. Circe struggles to find her place amongst the Gods and eventually finds power in witchcraft. The story tells of the actions and events that lead up to (and beyond) Circe's eventual banishment to the island of Aeaea where we know her best in the epic tale of the Odyssey. This is a pretty basic summary but I do not want to give too much away :)As we know next to nothing of Circe's life beyond her connection with Odysseus in the original Greek myths, there are liberties taken in this story and the author does a masterful job of weaving other Greek mythological tales within the life of Circe. I do not mind the liberties taken--they are myths!...more

review: 4.5 Stars-- I love Old Hollywood so this book captured my attention the entire time! Evelyn Hugo is possibly a mix of Elizabeth Taylor, Rita Hayworth,4.5 Stars-- I love Old Hollywood so this book captured my attention the entire time! Evelyn Hugo is possibly a mix of Elizabeth Taylor, Rita Hayworth, Greta Garbo and Ava Gardner with a twist. According to the author, Ava Gardner actually started a tell-all book with a ghostwriter and placed an excerpt in Vanity Fair. She was persuaded not to publish it but it later leaked after her death-- hence the inspiration. "They go to bed with Gilda; they wake up with me."- Rita Hayworth Such a simple but yet profound quote that encapsulates the truth of all famous people-- we don't really know them. This story follows the life of bombshell actress Evelyn Hugo in her own words. On the outside, she lived a glamorous life but the truth is messier and less picture perfect. The story of her memoir's writer, Monique Grant, is stronger at first but fizzles within until ending with a bang. I cannot share too much of synopsis without giving it away. I will say I appreciated the author's choice of including many of the Old Hollywood (and sadly today's too) taboo issues in the story. All in all, this is an entertaining and easy read....more

review: Sadly this is my first Ann Patchett book. When living in Nashville, I used to visit her bookstore "Parnassus Books" whenever I was in the Green Hills Sadly this is my first Ann Patchett book. When living in Nashville, I used to visit her bookstore "Parnassus Books" whenever I was in the Green Hills area (highly recommended if you are ever there!!!). However, I could never quite get myself to read one of her books, so THANK YOU San Diego Book Divas for adding Bel Canto to your list!! Now the book. I want to give this a 3.5. This story is beautifully written and I liked it, I just had a hard time keeping engaged in the plot. For a story about a hostage situation (inspired by the 1996 Lima Crisis), it's rather subdued. The hostage event starts off in the typically chaotic, violent mess but then settles into an almost utopian like housebound life where both sides just settle into their fate. This idealistic hostage life is mostly due to the lovely operatic singing of the lovely Roxane Coss. Apparently, she's spell-binding. This is where the story was lost on me because as much as I love good music and understand the need to hold on to something beautiful during a crisis, opera is just not my cup of tea. I did enjoy the interrelationships of the hostages and terrorists. Patchett did well showing that all "sides" are human beings. ...more

review: I am wavering between a 4 and 5 stars on this one---so 4.5. This is not the first book I've read where a virus/sickness has pushed the planet to apocaI am wavering between a 4 and 5 stars on this one---so 4.5. This is not the first book I've read where a virus/sickness has pushed the planet to apocalyptic status (wink wink nudge nudge "Station Eleven"). However, I really appreciated following ONE main character through this dystopian hell the whole way! The Unnamed Midwife or Jane or Dusty or whatever you want to call her is a likable and relatable character. I hope I would be as strong and smart as her in order to survive BUT to be honest, probably not. I would, however, have her amazing inner dialogue and feelings about others ;) and write them in a journal for others to read for all time! She sees some awful things and has to deal with some inhumane people (men). I wish I could say people wouldn't act like this -- but let's be honest. This is a well-written book and I look forward to reading the rest of the series. ...more
